// Vitest Snapshot v1, https://vitest.dev/guide/snapshot.html

exports[`cardFormatter golden snapshots > renders EARNINGS_ask_en.json unchanged 1`] = `
"<div style="font-family: -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', sans-serif; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb; border-radius: 10px; background: #fff; padding: 18px;"><div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; margin-bottom: 6px;"><div style="font-size: 18px; font-weight: 700; color: #111827;">📞 Earnings Q&A</div><span style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 600; padding: 2px 8px; border-radius: 9999px; background: #f3f4f6; color: #374151; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Ask Checkit</span></div><div style="font-size: 13px; color: #6b7280; margin-bottom: 14px;">NVDA</div><div style="margin-bottom: 12px; padding: 12px; background: #eff6ff; border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid #bfdbfe;">
    <div style="font-size: 12px; font-weight: 700; color: #1d4ed8; margin-bottom: 6px;">Answer</div>
    <div style="font-size: 14px; color: #1f2937; line-height: 1.7;" class="ask-card-answer"><p><strong>NVDA Q4 2026 — Analyst Q&amp;A</strong></p><p><strong>Q&amp;A 1 — Vivek Arya, Bank of America Securities</strong></p><ul><li>Question: How confident is NVIDIA in its cloud customers&#39; ability to sustain high capital expenditure growth, given concerns about their cash flow compression? Can NVIDIA grow even if customer CapEx plateaus?</li><li>Response: Jensen Huang expressed high confidence in customer cash flow growth. He argued that in the AI era, compute directly equals revenue, as tokens (generated by AI) are profitable and drive customer income. The inflection point for productive and profitable agentic AI has been reached, creating a fundamental shift where investment in compute capacity is essential for revenue growth, making sustained CapEx likely.</li><li>Sentiment: 9/10</li></ul><p><strong>Q&amp;A 2 — Joseph Moore, Morgan Stanley</strong></p><ul><li>Question: What is the strategic role of NVIDIA&#39;s investments (e.g., in Anthropic, OpenAI, CoreWeave, and partners like Intel) and how is the balance sheet used to strengthen the ecosystem?</li><li>Response: Investments are strategically focused on expanding and deepening NVIDIA&#39;s ecosystem across the entire AI stack. As NVIDIA evolves from a GPU computing platform to a full AI infrastructure company, it aims to ensure all emerging ecosystems (enterprise, industrial, scientific, robotics) are built on its platform. The goal is to leverage NVIDIA&#39;s position at the start of a new computing era to embed its technology broadly.</li><li>Sentiment: 8/10</li></ul><p><strong>Q&amp;A 3 — Harlan Sur, JPMorgan</strong></p><ul><li>Question: What is the current and projected run-rate for the Spectrum-X Ethernet switching platform, given strong networking growth and upcoming new products like Spectrum-6?</li><li>Response: Networking is a core part of NVIDIA&#39;s AI infrastructure. The NVLink scale-up technology has turbocharged the business, as each rack contains many switches. NVIDIA is now likely the largest Ethernet networking company in the world, with Spectrum-X being a major success. Performance advantages (e.g., 10-20% better data center efficiency) translate directly to significant customer value, driving rapid growth in the networking business.</li><li>Sentiment: 9/10</li></ul><p><strong>Q&amp;A 4 — Christopher Muse, Cantor Fitzgerald</strong></p><ul><li>Question: How will NVIDIA&#39;s future roadmap incorporate customized silicon for specific workloads (like large context windows or decode), especially with the Grok acquisition and move to chiplets?</li><li>Response: NVIDIA prioritizes architectural compatibility and efficiency, avoiding chiplets unless necessary to minimize latency and power. The strategy is to extend the NVIDIA architecture with Grok&#39;s low-latency decoder technology, similar to how Mellanox was integrated. Maintaining architectural compatibility across generations (like Ampere, Hopper, Blackwell) allows massive software investments to benefit the entire installed base, delivering superior performance per watt and dollar.</li><li>Sentiment: 8/10</li></ul><p><strong>Q&amp;A 5 — Stacy Rasgon, Bernstein Research</strong></p><ul><li>Question: How should we model sequential revenue growth through the year, especially with the Vera Rubin ramp in the second half? Also, can the Gaming segment grow year-over-year in fiscal 2027 despite supply constraints?</li><li>Response: For revenue, both Blackwell and Vera Rubin will be sold concurrently, with strong demand for both. The Rubin ramp in the second half is underway, but it&#39;s too early to quantify its exact contribution. For Gaming, supply constraints (particularly memory) are expected to be a headwind for several quarters. Year-over-year growth is possible if supply improves by year-end, but it&#39;s too early to confirm.</li><li>Sentiment: 7/10</li></ul><p><strong>Q&amp;A 6 — Atif Malik, Citi</strong></p><ul><li>Question: How important is CUDA as AI investment shifts more toward inference workloads?</li><li>Response: CUDA is critically important for inference. It enables software stacks like TensorRT Large Language Model and new parallelization algorithms to leverage hardware like NVLink 72, delivering massive generational leaps (e.g., 50x better performance per watt). Inference performance directly translates to customer revenue, as tokens are monetized. In power-constrained data centers, architecture with the best performance per watt (enabled by CUDA) maximizes revenue per watt, making it a strategic choice.</li><li>Sentiment: 9/10</li></ul><p><strong>Q&amp;A 7 — Benjamin Reitzes, Melius Research</strong></p><ul><li>Question: Can gross margins in the mid-70s be sustained long-term, given supply visibility into calendar 2027? What innovations could support margins beyond that?</li><li>Response: The key lever for sustaining gross margins is delivering unmatched generational leaps in performance per watt and performance per dollar to customers, exceeding Moore&#39;s Law. NVIDIA&#39;s strategy of annual AI infrastructure updates and extreme co-design aims to provide this value. The exponential growth in compute demand for AI ensures the value of these advancements, supporting margin sustainability as long as NVIDIA maintains its performance leadership.</li><li>Sentiment: 8/10</li></ul><p><strong>Q&amp;A 8 — Antoine Chkaiban, New Street Research</strong></p><ul><li>Question: What is the feasibility, horizon, and economics of space data centers, and what are the potential applications?</li><li>Response: The economics are currently poor but will improve. Computing in space faces different challenges (e.g., heat dissipation via conduction/radiators, no liquid cooling). A key application is on-orbit AI processing for high-resolution imaging, where it&#39;s more efficient to process petabytes of data in space to identify interesting events rather than transmitting all data to Earth. NVIDIA already has GPUs (Hopper) in space for such purposes.</li><li>Sentiment: 6/10</li></ul><p><strong>Q&amp;A 9 — Mark Lipacis, Evercore ISI</strong></p><ul><li>Question: Did non-hyperscale customers grow faster than hyperscalers (over 50% of revenue)? What are they doing differently, and will this trend continue, making them a larger part of the business?</li><li>Response: Yes, the diverse set of customers beyond the top five cloud providers/hyperscalers (including AI model makers, enterprises, supercomputing, sovereign nations) is growing very fast. NVIDIA&#39;s strength is its CUDA-based ecosystem, which makes its platform ubiquitous across clouds, on-premises data centers, edge, and robotics. This diversity, fueled by partnerships with major AI companies and support for open source, is a major advantage and is expected to continue.</li><li>Sentiment: 8/10</li></ul><p><strong>Q&amp;A 10 — Aaron Rakers, Wells Fargo</strong></p><ul><li>Question: What is the strategic importance of the Vera CPU as a standalone solution in NVIDIA&#39;s architecture evolution, especially for inference workloads?</li><li>Response: The Vera CPU is architected differently, focusing on high data processing capabilities and single-threaded performance, optimized for data-driven AI workloads. It plays crucial roles in the AI pipeline: data pre-processing, post-training where AI models use tools (often in CPU environments), and accelerating algorithms where fast CPUs are needed per Amdahl&#39;s Law. Vera is designed to be exceptional for these tasks, complementing GPUs.</li><li>Sentiment: 8/10</li></ul><p><strong>Q&amp;A 11 — Timothy Arcuri, UBS</strong></p><ul><li>Question: Given strong cash generation and a subdued stock price, why not implement a much larger share repurchase program instead of focusing on strategic investments?</li><li>Response: Capital return is carefully considered. The priority is to make strategic investments to support the expansive ecosystem, including securing supply chain capacity and fostering early AI development on NVIDIA&#39;s platform. Share repurchases and dividends continue, and the company will seek unique opportunities for buybacks, but balancing investment for long-term growth is paramount.</li><li>Sentiment: 7/10</li></ul><p><strong>Q&amp;A 12 — James Schneider, Goldman Sachs</strong></p><ul><li>Question: What key application areas (physical AI, agentic AI, etc.) are likely to drive the acceleration toward the previously outlined $3 to $4 trillion data center CapEx potential by 2030? Is that target still valid?</li><li>Response: The thesis remains valid. The shift to token-driven, generative AI software requires orders of magnitude more compute than classical software. Compute capacity directly drives customer revenue (tokens are monetized). The current wave is the agentic AI inflection (e.g., coding agents). The next major wave is physical AI (robotics, manufacturing). As long as token generation is the future of computing—which it is—the world will continue to invest heavily in AI factory infrastructure.</li><li>Sentiment: 9/10</li></ul></div>
  </div></div>"
`;

